{"actual_usd":0.15869,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":191,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31165,"reply":"\"No—neither of those, actually.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light, because this is one of those places where a tidy analogy usually makes a mess.*\n\n\"Christians mean one God in three Persons: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Holy Spirit is God—but the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father.\" *I lift a hand a little, like I’m trying to keep three things distinct without letting them drift apart.* \"So not three gods. And not one Person wearing three masks, either. The water thing sounds helpful for about ten seconds, but it slips into 'one thing changing forms,' and that’s not the claim.\" \n\n\"The strange part is, the doctrine is weirder and sturdier than the analogy: one divine being, three distinct Persons, together forever—not taking turns.\"","rolling_24h_usd":37.450205000000025,"run_id":"d24bc9d0-70a4-4a50-95b7-a5b4f518985b"}
